Au-delà des lunettes et au-delà du e-commerce, le Virtual Try-On a sa place dans le parcours clients (d'autant plus aujourd'hui avec le contexte sanitaire qui nous encourage à ne pas aller en boutique). Le Virtual Try-On est ludique, et permet de mieux se projeter dans son achat, il rassure. Il peut effectivement être utilisé en ecommerce, pour désengorger les points de vente physique et attirer de nouveaux clients. Mais également en boutique, pour pallier à l'absence de produit en stock, pour tester un full make up (sans avoir à se demaquiller en repartant) ou des vêtements quand les cabines d'essayage sont prises.
Attention cependant à ses limites : pour que les utilisateurs adhèrent, il faut que l'expérience soit parfaite ! Précision des mouvements de l'utilisateur, capteur pour "fitter" au mieux (couleur de peau, corpulence, forme du visage)... Et pourquoi ne pas aller plus loin en proposant des "vous allez aimé" en fonction de ses précédents achats / son apparence
Great idea which could make the online purchase experience easier. However, need some improvements to be as real as possible to replace a physical try in a store.

Virtual Try-On technology is a great and innovative idea. It needs some improvements to become a staple of the customer experience. For example :
- more efficient processing for potential customers with lower end devices,
- improved communication about the feature so that people are aware of its availability,
- added functionality such as uploading a photo for reduced data usage.
There is also concern surrounding the data collection with AR technologies like this one. It already relies on facial recognition which is already controversial and increasingly so.

I think this is an excellent idea, as it saves you from having to go to the shop, which is convenient especially in these times of health crisis when contact with objects must be minimised as much as possible. On the other hand, as far as I am concerned, I don't like going to the shop to buy sunglasses for two reasons.  Having someone who advises me bothers me and makes me feel uncomfortable because I find that I don't have a "head for sunglasses" and because I also find that tastes vary so much from person to person that I have rarely been satisfied with the options I have been offered. Secondly, because after making the trip and after being advised by someone from the brand (and more often than not you are accompanied when it comes to buying glasses by friends or family), there is a kind of buying pressure that sets in that I don't like. 
As a result, I prefer to buy glasses through websites. But until now, no one has offered to try them on virtually, I love the idea and it helps a lot! It's also very reassuring.

From a store point of view, using Virtual Try-On is a great idea, especially to target Millenials who LOVE to see themselves on camera and often feel like they look better on it. If they try a product virtually and it's a match, then they're more likely to buy it. And they will probably value their opinions more than the advice of a retail sales worker, anyway. Plus, let's not forget that we are lazy as fuck and/or busy af, so using VT-O could save us both time and effort. We don't have to go to the mall to try a product. Yay! Let's Netflix and chill instead. 

For the eldest generations, VT-O can be both a technological and cultural challenge. They might not understand how it works, how to use it or, because they don't have a great vision, they might not even see the result. 
Older people tend to appreciate human interaction. They are used to seek advice from retail sales person, they are used to go to the store/shop and try it on directly on them and not through a screen.

Being an old soul in a young body, I think VT-O is a good feature/option to have access to. I might even use it. But it won't be enough for me to decide whether to buy that product or not. I would still go to the store myself and try it on directly. Especially if the price is high. Virtual reality can be a trick haha. I want to know exactly where I put my money on, and be sure that the product really fits. So I would probably double-check with true tangible reality.

Now, because of that COVID crisis and the fact that we can no longer try-on directly in the shop, VT-O tends to be very appreciated (safer and better than nothing).

One last limitation of VT-O for the road... What about jeans or clothes, uh? You don't have the front/back view. You can't choose the right size either. So, obviously it doesn't work with every type of product.

I was bespectacled from 4th grade so have been using specs for quite sometime now. Being young and digitally strong I never thought of buying specs online because there are chances that the ordered specs might not suit me and mess up the way I look and don't want to take a chance since it's a long-term investment.

This changed after one of the Indian company named Lenskart introduced virtual try-on feature. Based on my face shape it used to suggest me frames that suit me.

There are couple of cons such as data privacy but I belive the pros can outweigh the cons
